{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "This collection of essays addresses the topic of the unity of knowledge by analyzing early modern ways of organizing and systematizing knowledge and by bringing to light the complex interactions between the different traditions which contributed to the making of modernity.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Smith depicts knowledge as the result of a mathematically-inspired method applicable to all subject-matters.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "He contends that an interpretation of mathesis has to stand on its own merits and recommends placing this concept in a broader historical perspective, by looking at its uses both before Descartes (emphasizing its Renaissance uses) and after (all the way to Husserl and Heidegger).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Elodie Cassan maintains that neither DescartesÕ emphasis on deduction nor his use of ÔhypothesesÕ undermines his scientific realism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "According to Vlad Alexandrescu in ÔThe Double Question of the Individuation of Physical Bodies in DescartesÕ, despite doing away with the matter/form schema, Descartes is not stuck with a homogenous, continuous world but rather devises two ways of individuating bodies.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Roger Ariew (ÔDescartes and Leibniz on the Principle of IndividuationÕ) compares LeibnizÕs and DescartesÕ positions on individuation and traces them back to Scholastic positions thus diminishing their claims to originality.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Petrescu takes the issue of memory as a focal point for properly treating the relation between these three areas of Cartesian thought.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Spinoza intended to reduce not just natural philosophy but also religion, morals, law and politics to foundational basic mechanical principles which are self-evident and clearly and distinctly perceived.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Gaukroger thinks that SpinozaÕs system crumbles because its foundational principles are mistaken and it lacks an adaptive feedback feature.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Locke rejects the use of hypotheses aimed at uncovering the hidden nature of things since (like his contemporaries Walter Charleton, Joseph Glanvill, Thomas Sprat and RobertHooke) he opposes speculative systembuilding at the expense of observation and experience.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Carefully circumscribing inquiry to the realm of experience brings us closer to God, so the counterpart of LockeÕs natural historical method is an act of natural religion.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Dana Jalobeanu accounts for the popularity of BaconÕs Sylva Sylvarum and the New Atlantis in terms of the efficacy of BaconÕs model for communicating knowledge.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Igor Agostini (ÔCaterus on God as Òens a seÓÕ) maintains that the Cartesian view of positive divine aseity was criticized by Caterus not for its original and unheard of character but rather because it was an attempt to resurrect a view that had already been shown to be untenable (since involving a contradiction).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "In ÔDescartes and Henry More on Living BodiesÕ, Justin Smith takes differences over the nature and causes of life as the main reason why, despite MoreÕs enthusiasm, no real dialogue took place between More and Descartes.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "To conclude, this anthology presents the unity of knowledge as overarching systems of knowledge based on fundamental principles and as tightly connected disciplines.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Finally, this anthology portrays modernity as the result of the intersection, collision and mingling of Aristotelian Scholasticism, Lullism, Ramism, Neoplatonism, mechanism, experimental philosophy and Cartesianism.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
  "relations": [
    {
